@Matt I looked at them and yes, the KeyError is because the format string specifies a keyword that isn't in the dictionary.

The format error happens when the format string uses keywords, but you don't pass a dictionary.   Though I'm surprised that event wasn't considered a dictionary."}, {'account_id': 6601, 'date': '2014-03-07 22:20:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

I had to update my clone.  I see now that the iteritems() is just syntactic sugar and event isn't really a dictionary, so format can't tell that it is.

So I think this update looks good."}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2014-03-07 22:33:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I see that the log module in oslo is converting context to a dict if it needs to:

https://github.com/openstack/oslo-incubator/blob/master/openstack/common/log.py#L220

Wonder if something like that needs to be done for nova objects, but we obviously can't put nova objects stuff in oslo."}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2014-03-08 14:40:16.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

I can't say I completely understand this, but I want to get debug logging enabled in unit tests so we catch more stuff early.  Would be nice to have a better understanding of why objects aren't treated like dicts by the log formatter."}, {'account_id': 6601, 'date': '2014-03-08 21:34:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

@Matt, I did a bit more research.  It looks like what __mod__ does when it encounters a keyword in the format string is call __getitem__ on the passed parameter with that keyword.  So as long as the object passed as the parameter supports __getitem__ it will work.  For example, if only instance attributes(1) need to be supported, an object could use an implementation like: 

    def __getitem__(self, key):
        return self.__dict__[key]

(1) Class instances section description of __dict__ in http://docs.python.org/2/reference/datamodel.html#the-standard-type-hierarchy'}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2014-03-09 14:13:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Hmm, nova objects do implement __getitem__:

https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/master/nova/objects/base.py#L380'}, {'account_id': 6463, 'date': '2014-03-10 01:34:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

'}, {'account_id': 6601, 'date': '2014-03-10 17:27:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@Matt it is a subtle yet important difference was that I was looking at LOG.debug(msg % event) and this does LOG.debug(msg, event).   In the first case it is formatting which works with the parameter and uses __getitem__ and in the 2nd case it is the logger that works with it.   I believe that because the logger adds some additional keyword arguments when logging, it requires that the parameter is a dictionary (I didn't determine exactly what check it was making to determine if the parameter is a dictionary).

So another fix for this problem would be to apply formatting immediately using 'event' versus having to pass logging 'dict(event.iteritems())'."}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2014-03-10 17:39:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Looks good to me (core reviewer); Approved

commit_message:
Fix debug message formatting in server_external_events

Hopefully this will be the last case of invalid debug log messages to
fix before turning on debug level log messages on during unit tests, so
we can gate on issues like this.

Change-Id: I8a2b64222deaf5320bcc2e5215b6bd46565a505f

commit_message:
Add host_routes property to Neutron subnet resource

Template snippet that was functionally tested:

subnet:
  Type: OS::Neutron::Subnet
  Properties:
    host_routes:
    - {destination: 192.168.1.0/24, nexthop: 192.168.1.2}
    network_id: {Ref: network}
    ip_version: 4
    cidr: 10.0.3.0/24
    allocation_pools:
    - {end: 10.0.3.150, start: 10.0.3.20}

(Next hop probably would make more sense to be in the CIDR)

Change-Id: I36f72f006a1ba48a6ed55a1c361b3df8d1359caa
Closes-Bug: #1250710

commit_message:
Use instance object instead of _instance_update()

Currently, if a user takes a snapshot of a VM, stops nova-cpu
before the snapshot operation is finished, and restart nova-cpu:
nova-cpu will crash with the error:
AttributeError: 'dict' object has no attribute 'task_state'
This happens because the _instance_update() method returns a dict
and not an Instance object.

This patch fixes the issue by not using _instance_update()
in the compute manager which is returning a dict and using
the instance object instead.

Change-Id: I3af0b09aeff7790b147a684f7c90af17d8ee7ae2
Closes-Bug: #1287945

'}, {'created': '2014-02-18 00:24:58.000000000', 'message': 'Resource type implementation for software deployment

Some notes on the implementation:
  * SoftwareDeployment is a SignalResponder so that it can receive
    output value updates from the server via curl or cfn-signal
  * By default, SoftwareDeployment remains in an IN_PROGRESS state
    until a signal is received
  * If wait_for_signal=False the resource will go immediately to COMPLETE
  * A deployment resource can be configured to deploy on any action.
    By default it deploys on CREATE and UPDATE
  * The outputs deploy_stderr, deploy_stdout and deploy_status_code
    are defined in the attributes schema, but other attributes map to
    whatever outputs are defined for the corresponding config resource
  * The resource will go into a FAILED state if an error_output output
    has a value, or if deploy_status_code is non-zero

Implements: blueprint hot-software-config

Change-Id: I97df5651dc6f27ed4ddc7355c21ab61270b15b68

'}, {'created': '2014-02-25 21:26:21.000000000', 'message': "Resource type implementation for software deployment

Some notes on the implementation:
  * Whenever a config should be deployed, this resource loads the config
    and creates an ephemeral derived config which has the following inputs
    added to it:
    * deploy_server_id
    * deploy_action
    * deploy_signal_id
    These inputs can be used by the hook *or* by the configuration script
    itself.
  * The ephemeral config also has the current input values inserted into
    the 'value' field of the config inputs. This allows the deployment
    metadata to be a simple list of configs.
  * Subclasses of SoftwareDeployment can make further transformations to
    the ephemeral config, such as transforming the config script to contain
    input values.
  * SoftwareDeployment is a SignalResponder so that it can receive
    output value updates from the server via curl or cfn-signal
  * By default, SoftwareDeployment remains in an IN_PROGRESS state
    until a signal is received
  * If wait_for_signal=False the resource will go immediately to COMPLETE
  * A deployment resource can be configured to deploy on any action.
    By default it deploys on CREATE and UPDATE
  * The outputs deploy_stderr, deploy_stdout and deploy_status_code
    are defined in the attributes schema, but other attributes map to
    whatever outputs are defined for the corresponding config resource
  * The resource will go into a FAILED state if an error_output output
    has a value, or if deploy_status_code is non-zero

Implements: blueprint hot-software-config

Change-Id: I97df5651dc6f27ed4ddc7355c21ab61270b15b68

"}, {'created': '2014-02-27 05:58:40.000000000', 'message': "Resource type implementation for software deployment

Some notes on the implementation:
  * Whenever a config should be deployed, this resource loads the config
    and creates an ephemeral derived config which has the following inputs
    added to it:
    * deploy_server_id
    * deploy_action
    * deploy_signal_id
    * deploy_stack_id
    These inputs can be used by the hook *or* by the configuration script
    itself.
  * The ephemeral config also has the current input values inserted into
    the 'value' field of the config inputs. This allows the deployment
    metadata to be a simple list of configs.
  * Subclasses of SoftwareDeployment can make further transformations to
    the ephemeral config, such as transforming the config script to contain
    input values.
  * SoftwareDeployment is a SignalResponder so that it can receive
    output value updates from the server via curl or cfn-signal
  * By default, SoftwareDeployment remains in an IN_PROGRESS state
    until a signal is received
  * If wait_for_signal=False the resource will go immediately to COMPLETE
  * A deployment resource can be configured to deploy on any action.
    By default it deploys on CREATE and UPDATE
  * The outputs deploy_stderr, deploy_stdout and deploy_status_code
    are defined in the attributes schema, but other attributes map to
    whatever outputs are defined for the corresponding config resource
  * The resource will go into a FAILED state if an error_output output
    has a value, or if deploy_status_code is non-zero
  * If the 'name' property is set, this will set the 'name' property
    of the derived config, which will determine the sort order of configs
    returned when fetching a list of config metadata for a given server.
  * When an input_value is set where there is no corresponding config inputs
    schema entry, the derived config will add those input schemas to the
    derived input. This allows some templates to be more DRY.

Implements: blueprint hot-software-config

  * When an input_value is set where there is no corresponding config
    inputs schema entry, the derived config will add those input schemas
    to the derived input. This allows some templates to be more DRY.

commit_message:
Resource type implementation for software deployment

Some notes on the implementation:
  * Whenever a config should be deployed, this resource loads the config
    and creates an ephemeral derived config which has the following inputs
    added to it:
    * deploy_server_id
    * deploy_action
    * deploy_stack_id
    * deploy_resource_name
  * When signal_transport=CFN_SIGNAL, the folling input is added:
    * deploy_signal_id
  * When signal_transport=HEAT_SIGNAL, the folling inputs are added:
    * deploy_auth_url
    * deploy_username
    * deploy_password
    * deploy_project_id
    These inputs can be used by the hook *or* by the configuration script
    itself.
  * The ephemeral config also has the current input values inserted into
    the 'value' field of the config inputs. This allows the deployment
    metadata to be a simple list of configs.
  * Subclasses of SoftwareDeployment can make further transformations to
    the ephemeral config, such as transforming the config script to contain
    input values.
  * SoftwareDeployment is a SignalResponder so that it can receive
    output value updates from the server via curl or cfn-signal
  * By default, SoftwareDeployment remains in an IN_PROGRESS state
    until a signal is received
  * If wait_for_signal=False the resource will go immediately to COMPLETE
  * A deployment resource can be configured to deploy on any action.
    By default it deploys on CREATE and UPDATE
  * The outputs deploy_stderr, deploy_stdout and deploy_status_code
    are defined in the attributes schema, but other attributes map to
    whatever outputs are defined for the corresponding config resource
  * The resource will go into a FAILED state if an error_output output
    has a value, or if deploy_status_code is non-zero
  * If the 'name' property is set, this will set the 'name' property
    of the derived config, which will determine the sort order of configs
    returned when fetching a list of config metadata for a given server.
  * When an input_value is set where there is no corresponding config
    inputs schema entry, the derived config will add those input schemas
    to the derived input. This allows some templates to be more DRY.

Implements: blueprint hot-software-config

Change-Id: I97df5651dc6f27ed4ddc7355c21ab61270b15b68

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-03-04 06:35:29.000000000', 'message': "Remove signal_id from deployments API and model

The same information is now available from the deployment's
derived config deploy_signal_id input value.

Other deployment signal transports might not have a single ID
to put in this field so it is better at this stage to remove

commit_message:
Remove signal_id from deployments API and model

The same information is now available from the deployment's
derived config deploy_signal_id input value.

Other deployment signal transports might not have a single ID
to put in this field so it is better at this stage to remove
it from the deployments model and do anything that is required
using derived config inputs.

partial blueprint hot-software-config

Change-Id: I90c85d0ceb9fd67eed640c84348ef4175a6194b6

commit_message:
Document Assignments feature

The assignments feature allows admins to separate role authorization
and user authentication when the Identity Service is configured to
use an LDAP back end. This patch adds instructions on how to do so.

Change-Id: I46d6b090ae126b880003020dc0eb9112a44dabb0
Closes-Bug: #1290629

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-03-05 06:54:40.000000000', 'message': 'Fix bad exception message output by %(message)s

Since 'message' is the same name as the second argument to the
constructor, 'message="Oorah"' is not a keyword argument.

Bad example:
  raise exception.VolumeDriverException(message="Oorah")
  ==> cinder.exception.VolumeDriverException: Oorah

Good example:
  raise exception.VolumeDriverException(message="Oorah")
  ==> cinder.exception.VolumeDriverException: Volume driver reported
      an error: Oorah

In cinder/utils.py, it is using the invalid keyword arguments as
follows. It is not intended probably.

  raise exception.InvalidInput(message=msg)

It is usually 'reason=msg', but since messages would change, put
only 'msg'.

Change-Id: I563e6d01128a8d37e9d31826bcbec38f2fc7609c
Closes-Bug: #1288066
'}]
commit_message:
Fix bad exception message output by %(message)s

Since 'message' is the same name as the second argument to the
constructor, 'message="Oorah"' is not a keyword argument.

Bad example:
  raise exception.VolumeDriverException(message="Oorah")
  ==> cinder.exception.VolumeDriverException: Oorah

Good example:
  raise exception.VolumeDriverException(message="Oorah")
  ==> cinder.exception.VolumeDriverException: Volume driver reported
      an error: Oorah

In cinder/utils.py, it is using the invalid keyword arguments as
follows. It is not intended probably.

  raise exception.InvalidInput(message=msg)

It is usually 'reason=msg', but since messages would change, put
only 'msg'.

Change-Id: I563e6d01128a8d37e9d31826bcbec38f2fc7609c
Closes-Bug: #1288066

commit_message:
Revert "Sync latest Oslo config code for i18n"

This reverts commit 9550b6b6b486559b7c89b94e7ffb20b794aaa795

Hate to do this but this seems to be the culprit for exposing some issues:
https://bugs.launchpad.net/cinder/+bug/1290503

Good news is it looks like the issue has been identified, the problem is
that we can't just fix it in Cinder, it needs fixed in OSLO, then synched again.

Also I'm not comfortable given all the hidden issues that this seems to have
exposed adding this in this late in the release cycle.

Change-Id: I58a43c77e1adda52f9984203697e0ccf97cda235

commit_message:
Adds nfs-server element

This patch adds an element that installs and configures nfs
services for testing the cinder nfs backend in an environment
where no nfs services are present (e.g. CI)

When added to an image, this element creates a directory at
/mnt/state/var/lib/nfs and shares it to each node of the
overcloud.

This patch that handles the package mapping in diskimage-builder
needs to be applied first: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/76398/.

Change-Id: I4c425af64b866caa80b32b808e8a3b97d71ca81d

commit_message:
Fix retry logic

When passing retry=True to verify_uuid_token this later should
re-call it self when the method fail and this time with retry=False.

Change-Id: I7e8f478e5116ac4119df134587f29f3f25ae8a42
Closes-Bug: #1285847

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-11-04 14:36:55.000000000', 'message': 'test external connectivity scenario/network_basic

add test cases for external connectivity against google servers
ping ip (8.8.8.8) and url (www.google.com) thus testing external
connection and dns configuration respectively

external destination (ip, url) is set as constant
TODO(yfried):
	1. add external conectivity flag to tempest.conf
	2. add external destination to tempest.conf
suggestions on this are more than welcome

helper changes:
scenario manger:
	moved _ssh_to_server()
	and

commit_message:
Increase testing of network connectivity

Adds ping against VM's internal network elements:
need all of them because agents might be located on different hosts
    1. Router port
    2. DHCP port

Adds ping against public network default gateway implying external
connectivity. Any further network tests are outside the Openstack cloud and the
testing environment

Partially Implements: blueprint neutron-advanced-scenarios

Change-Id: I9aaba5496581c9e3472d7a3846b1a0464f6334e6

commit_message:
Give the seed and undercloud more IPs to work with

We have a /24 range to work with, and would like to support seed
->overcloud for test performance. This requires enough IPs to
deploy the overcloud to be available on the seed.

Change-Id: I05a9d2fc70e10870b777590ea4841cc44c33f974

System need libffi-dev

The system need libffi-dev to allow pip to install
all dependencies.

Closes-Bug: 1286167

commit_message:
Add options to use remove_unused_* parameters

Being able to modify the parameters "remove_unused_base_images",
"remove_unused_original_minimum_age_seconds",
"remove_unused_kernels", "remove_unused_resized_minimum_age_seconds"
if desired.

Change-Id: Ia24594ccc4b999674456e59a279e2d5916cd5d7a
Implements: blueprint add-remove-unused-parameters

Thanks Mark for pointing me that its not good idea to import one migration script to another. 

Even though the main focus of this patch was to refactor the code to make all the BadStoreUri exceptions thrown from 'legacy_parse_uri' logged along with its respective image_id's, I found the 'legacy_parse_uri' function being duplicated and hence included the removal of duplication too (for which I had to import one migration script into another) as part of this patch set.

Need your suggestion if I can submit another patch set for review that includes only changes for logging image_id along with BadStoreURI(without including the removal of duplication of 'legacy_parse_uri' function changes).

Thank you Mark, Alex, Iccha and Arnaud for reviewing this patch and leaving your valuable comments."}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2014-01-24 06:03:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Abandoned

commit_message:
Log 'image_id' with all BadStoreURI error messages

- handle all BadStoreUri exceptions raised by 'legacy_parse_uri'
  function in
one location so that it becomes easier to log the error message with
'image_id'
- add tests for 'legacy_parse_uri'

Closes-Bug: #1243704

Change-Id: Ifc5de11832860ed51c1eb359d6f5cf78de8c0ba4

commit_message:
3PAR: Support extend volume based on snapshot

If extend volume fails with an HTTP Forbidden error 150,
convert the volume to a base volume and retry extending.

Change-Id: Id407058e954b2630f4a7f31c6149361301b502f2
Closes-Bug: #1285906

commit_message:
Add driver certificate test requirement

This provides a new driver requirement in passing certificate tests to
ensure tempest tests pass with actual backends.

Change-Id: I2635c1e313c9d1a737d6d28b62c593c5d27c3d44

commit_message:
Revert "Sync latest Oslo config code for i18n"

This reverts commit 9550b6b6b486559b7c89b94e7ffb20b794aaa795

Hate to do this but this seems to be the culprit for exposing some issues:
https://bugs.launchpad.net/cinder/+bug/1290503

Good news is it looks like the issue has been identified, the problem is that we can't just fix it in Cinder, it needs fixed in OSLO, then synched again.  Also I'm not comfortable given all the hidden issues that this seems to have exposed adding this in this late in the release cycle.

commit_message:
Create secret - case insensitive Content-Type check

Allows for upper case and mixed case types, subtypes, and parameters
in the Content-Type header field as per RFC 1341. More details can
be found at http://www.w3.org/Protocols/rfc1341/4_Content-Type.html.

Closes-Bug: #1252453
Change-Id: I400a05593e0c622de93a47a0fe0394793eb777f1

commit_message:
Sync latest Oslo config code for i18n

This sync pulls the latest Oslo config code over
to Cinder.  This sync is needed to include a fix
to config generator which is needed as part of
the work to enabled i18n messages.  Config generator
was failing when lazy message translation was enabled.

The following changes are included with this patch. Each
patch includes the file(s) the patch touches:
-> c178e56 Add basic Python 3 tests
--> cinder/openstack/common/__init__.py
-> 12bcdb7 Remove vim header
--> cinder/openstack/common/__init__.py
-> 547ab34 Fix Copyright Headers - Rename LLC to Foundation
--> cinder/openstack/common/__init__.py
-> 44b6ea3 Import oslo.config configuration file generator
--> cinder/openstack/common/config/__init__.py
-> dd9aa2b Remove unused variables
--> cinder/openstack/common/config/generator.py
-> 5dce17b Use entry points to discover options in libraries
--> tools/config/generate_sample.sh
--> cinder/openstack/common/config/generator.py
-> e8e636c generator: add an EXTRA_LIBRARIES env variable
--> cinder/openstack/common/config/generator.py
-> e3dddd7 generator: use EXTRA_* env vars in the bash script
--> tools/config/generate_sample.sh
--> cinder/openstack/common/config/generator.py
-> 6da13e8 generator: rename EXTRA_MODULES_FILE to RC_FILE
--> tools/config/generate_sample.sh
-> 763eedf Fix DictOpt support in config sample generator
--> cinder/openstack/common/config/generator.py
-> e839886 Config generator fails with lazy messages
--> cinder/openstack/common/config/generator.py
-> 343686b Add check_uptodate to tools/config
--> tools/config/check_uptodate.sh

Oslo version:
-> 0f24d82 Fix migration.db_version when no tables
-> Date: Sat, 22 Feb 2014 00:32:18 +0000

Change-Id: I26a95fe96b08d6340b0fce1b9e2949c8e661a946
Closes-Bug: 1280826
Related-bp: i18n-messages

commit_message:
Fix sqlachemy warning

This fixes the following warning:
SAWarning: Ignoring declarative-like tuple value of attribute timestamp:
possibly a copy-and-paste error with a comma left at the end of the line?

Change-Id: Ibda917862ffcc777d7c7d81f264e24e6511446fd
Fixes-Bug: #1286947

The import lines: 

from cinder.openstack.common.gettextutils import _

should be left alone.

The use of gettextutils.install('cinder', lazy=True) modifies the built-in, which can interfere with other modules that modify the build-in as well.   So the goal is to move to using only gettextutils.enable_lazy() and explicitly doing the import above whenever _ is used which does not require the modification of the built-in."}, {'account_id': 7198, 'date': '2014-02-12 21:56:19.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-02-12 21:56:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

This patch re-enables lazy translation to enable REST API
responses to be translated to the requested locale (I.E. setting
'Accept-Language: zh-CN'.)

This patch also removes the unnecessary manual import of
'cinder.openstack.common.gettextutils _' in Cinder code.  Since _ is
still being imported in the cinder.openstack.common files from Oslo
we still need to set gettexttutils.enable_lazy().  enable_lazy will
be able to be removed once the manual imports of _ have been removed
from Oslo.

"}, {'created': '2014-02-12 21:56:19.000000000', 'message': "Re-enable lazy translation

This patch re-enables lazy translation to enable REST API
responses to be translated to the requested locale (I.E. setting
'Accept-Language: zh-CN'.)

Rather than attempt to add 'from cinder.openstack.common.gettextutils import _'
to all of Cinder's files at this point in time, I have instead decided to
cover both possible approaches by setting both 'gettextutils.enable_lazy()'
and 'gettextutils.install('cinder', Lazy=true) .'  This will ensure proper
functionality regardless of the approach taken by the developer.
Moving cinder to manually importing _() can be undertaken via another patch
if deemed appropriate.

Change-Id: I0b5a35a2cc28d97d12ceccccd58565b487fef428
implements-bp: i18n-messages

commit_message:
Re-enable lazy translation

This patch re-enables lazy translation to enable REST API
responses to be translated to the requested locale (I.E. setting
'Accept-Language: zh-CN'.)

This patch also removes the unnecessary manual import of
'cinder.openstack.common.gettextutils _' in Cinder code.  Since _ is
still being imported in the cinder.openstack.common files from Oslo
we still need to set gettexttutils.enable_lazy().  enable_lazy will
be able to be removed once the manual imports of _ have been removed
from Oslo.

implements-bp: i18n-messages
Change-Id: I0b5a35a2cc28d97d12ceccccd58565b487fef428

commit_message:
Change lazy translation to retain complete dict

When replacement text was retained for later translation, only
the entries that were associated with the keywords in the
format string were retained.  There was a bug in how the keywords
were parsed.  This reduction was done to support the use of
locals() to specify the replacement text.  This is now prevented
by H501 (confirmed in all projects).

This means that instead of fixing the parsing code to correctly
find the keywords, the entire dictionary can now be retained
and the code for finding the keywords and stripping out unused
entries removed.

Change-Id: I7969dc20841d839f68b2ddb29ac47340c6b615e8
Closes-Bug: #1288049

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-02-20 12:49:29.000000000', 'message': 'Adds nfs share metadata to block-storage template

To support the changes to the cinder element to allow the nfs
backend to be utilized, the nfs_shares key has been added.
The value is a list of strings containing share addresses.

This change is added as a WIP to facilitate an example to test
the cinder element change: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/74563/

This patch hard codes the share address and needs to be updated to
match the actual address whether that is the control node or
another node.  Eventually this template will be changed to
reference the location of the share dynamically.

You may setup the nfs server manually or use the nfs-server
element (WIP) at https://review.openstack.org/#/c/74712/.

Change-Id: I5b6cb118b34421ea07a81ed1fe68db24b1d4f19d

commit_message:
Adds block-storage-nfs template

To support the changes to the cinder element to allow the nfs
backend to be utilized, this template has been added to show
the usage of the nfs_shares key in the cinder metadata.
The value is a list of strings containing share addresses.

This change is added to facilitate an example to test
the cinder element change: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/74563/

You may setup the nfs server manually or use the nfs-server
element at https://review.openstack.org/#/c/74712/.

Change-Id: I5b6cb118b34421ea07a81ed1fe68db24b1d4f19d

commit_message:
Adapt DB provisioning code for CI requirements

With recent changes made to our CI MySQL openstack_citest user now
has enough priviliges to create and drop databases. But the code,
that we use for provisioning of databases must be updated, so that
it's not mandatory for openstack_citest user to be also able to
do GRANT/ALTER ROLE queries. Actually this simplifies provisioning
code a bit and allows to reuse the same queries for PostgreSQL and
MySQL.

This will be used for opportunistic db test cases as well as for
running of DbTestCase tests on different backends.

commit_message:
Update oslo-incubator config module

Changes -
 * Sanitize FQDN in config generator
 * Config generator fails with lazy messages
 * Fix DictOpt support in config sample generator

Change-Id: I4644059b9a2bf7d6e6176029637bd83bac520fa4

commit_message:
Update oslo-incubator service module

Changes -
 * Add missing _LI for LOG.info in service module
 * notify calling process we are ready to serve
 * Reap child processes gracefully if greenlet thread gets killed
 * Update oslo log messages with translation domains

Change-Id: I6cdcdeeea7fa88e95939fb89fbbb1147696a359d

commit_message:
autohelp.py: handle oslo.messaging config options

This patch enables the automatic discovery of oslo.messaging configuration
options.

It uses stevedore to load the modules as is already done in the oslo.config
sample file generator: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/66955/

Change-Id: I4edf94344d3c6c0fce0de594191a2bbf7930557f

commit_message:
Prepare for enabling H302 rule(services/telemetry, object_storage, etc)

Currently H302 rule is ignored by tox. However, this rule should
be enabled. This patch partially fixes this problem to prepare for
H302 rule.

Change-Id: I5b2d2f872de7a1cb846d3002022ff7ffa613813a

commit_message:
Cisco Neutron plugin fails DB migration

Alembic migration from revision f44ab9871cd6 to 2eeaf963a447 fails
because the floatingips table doesn't exist.

The fix is to add the plugin to the DB migration path for l3 and ext_gw_mode.

Change-Id: Ic7a9c1d624d2838e9313fa95ed6ddbfea9b6e1c9
Closes-Bug: #1289039

that were setting options before calling super() have been

the Policy.json tests cannot be moved into config_overrides
due to the need to control how and when policy data is loaded.

commit_message:
Use config fixture

Use the configuration fixture instead of the old opt_in_group and
opt methods.

Where possible the config_fixture usage done from within setUp
has been moved to config_overrides() method. Notably a number of
the Policy.json tests cannot be moved into config_overrides
due to the need to control how and when policy data is loaded.

Change-Id: I1662627cca30890cc3f3da83772132cec7bd58e0

commit_message:
Adding support for Django 1.6

Horizon and django_openstack_auth 1.1.4 are both now compatible
with Django 1.6.  Bumping versions of Django to include 1.6 and
django_openstack_auth to force a Django 1.6 compatible version.

Partially-implements blueprint django-1point6

Change-Id: Id753ffa53d2484dab39e530de0a41e85f9e07742

(1 inline comment)

Hi, thanks for pointing me at this one Clint. 

There are 2 angles to this I think:
- Do we want to preserve the old behavior of using a packaged pip/virtualenv?
- Does this effect the existing package based installs?

First off, it sounds like it may not be a good idea to be using the distro's packaged pip to do OpenStack installs from source? Is it just the issue with mirrors that have wheels that old pip's can't talk to?  TBH, since we're already installing OpenStack from source in these scenarios, I'm not sure it much matters that we're using the packaged pip or not. I'd in fact be ok with not having an option for the old way from this perspective.

For the second point, in an all package based install, we do not want get-pip.py to be run. We can override the REPOTYPE for pip-and-virtualenv, but 01-install-pip-and-virtualenv is in pre-install.d and source-repositories only considers install.d when enabling different install types.

See http://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack/diskimage-builder/tree/elements/source-repositories/extra-data.d/98-source-repositories#n124

So, we have 2 options for that:
 - move 01-install-pip-and-virtualenv under install.d/pip-and-virtualenv-source-install/
 - Allow divergence for source and package installs in pre-install.d as well. Probably not too hard, just add a step to setup the symlinks the same way it is done for install.d"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-02-25 01:14:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Build failed.  For information on how to proceed, see https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/GerritJenkinsGit#Test_Failures

'}, {'account_id': 7144, 'date': '2014-02-25 21:21:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: (1 inline comment)

Ok, I tested this out to see if it was possible to override the pip download as-is. It *almost* is, we just need to change the first parameter in the source-repository file for pip-and-virtualenv (see inline comment).

After doing so, this worked to override the download:

  DIB_REPOTYPE_get_pip_py=package \
  ELEMENTS_PATH=../tripleo-image-elements/elements/ \
  bin/disk-image-create -a amd64 fedora pip-and-virtualenv

However, that is a little weird, since you don't actually end up install pip from package at that point. So, could we just add a pip-and-virtualenv/install.d/get-pip-py-package-install/01-install-pip-and-virtualenv that just does an "install-packages python-pip python-virtualenv"?

In fact, I went ahead and tested these changes out, and could submit a subsequent patchset to this review if wanted :-). 

Thought I'd hold off though in case there is strong opposition to preserving the old way as well? Let me know.'}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2014-02-26 09:40:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

@slagle,AIUI the argument is 'if using PIP, you always want the latest', so I'd say we have a binary situation:

 - we're using pip somewhere (including virtualenvs)
 - we're not

And thats independent of using packages.

So - I think we should make elements that use virtual envs depend on the new pip-and-virtualenv element, and that should unconditionally install pip from the configured pypi source.

What seems interesting to me is that the package approach today doesn't discriminate element dependencies based on installation type. What do you think of the idea of adding a condition to the dependency rule - e.g.

 pip-and-virtualenv [source]

would say 'when doing source installs use this element', and then package installs that don't use pip or virtualenv would not end up bringing in the element."}, {'account_id': 6969, 'date': '2014-02-26 12:39:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

James if you have the code ready I am happy if you want to push it up here and we can review it then. I might not fully understand all your packing issues so if you push it up I will test here against and make sure that it works for us.

Lifeless I have to read up on the conditional dependencies to comment future at the moment. But I am interest in seeing what James has first.'}, {'account_id': 7144, 'date': '2014-02-26 15:53:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

@lifeless, I'd be fine with that approach. It seems like more work, but should be doable. Would have to make element_dependencies.py a bit smarter in how it parses element-deps. Or, have it look for element-deps, and element-deps-source / element-deps-package files depending on the install type of the element.

Like I mentioned earlier, I'm not opposed to using the non-packaged pip/virtualenv for source installs. It makes sense to do so."}, {'account_id': 7144, 'date': '2014-02-26 15:58:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

The conditional dependency model is, I think, a refinement of what we already have that would allow us to not install unused pip/virtualenv on package based installs. [{'created': '2014-02-20 15:32:46.000000000', 'message': "Install latest version of pip and virtualenv

Install pip with get-pip.py and use this to install virtualenv.

We require this in order to talk to a pypi mirror generated with
a recent http://github.com/openstack-infra/pypi-mirror This mirror
caches some wheels that the previous version of pip & virtualenv can't
install.

virtualenv contains its own version of pip that is used for all virtualenv
environments.

Change-Id: I282fd8fffc8d5707a078f78f2b4571138d7266f3

commit_message:
Install latest version of pip and virtualenv

We install pip with get-pip.py and use this to install virtualenv. This
is done as part of the new pip-and-virtualenv element. All elements that
need pip or virtualenv should use this element to install them.

Our motivation is that we need to talk to a pypi mirror generated with
a recent http://github.com/openstack-infra/pypi-mirror This mirror
caches some 'wheels' that the previous version of pip & virtualenv
can't install.

virtualenv contains its own version of pip that is used for all
virtualenv environments.

Change-Id: I282fd8fffc8d5707a078f78f2b4571138d7266f3

commit_message:
Switch to SQLAlchemy 0.9

After SQLAlchemy-migrate has been fixed for SQLAlchemy 0.9,
and after the last problem (with Keystone) has been fixed,
we finally can switch to SQLAlchemy 0.9. It is important we
do the switch to SQLAlchemy 0.9.x ASAP, because that is what
distributions (eg: at least Debian) are using. This also
ensure we avoid any future mistakes if we do the gating with
SQLAlchemy 0.9.

This patch sets the cap from <=0.8.99 to <=0.9.99.

Change-Id: I9d2a9e0526359fa1e97df250a63f71496d47367a

[{'created': '2014-02-28 04:40:11.000000000', 'message': "Detect missing packages with yum

yum -y doesn't report an error when packages are missing (see [1] for
upstream discussion).  Thus we run the output of yum through a small
awk script looking for missing packages and fail with an exit code
that gets picked up by -e and halts the script.

The one change required for RHEL is that python-wsgiref is included in
the distro python, so doesn't need a separate package.

[1] https://bugzilla.redhat.com/show_bug.cgi?id=965567

Change-Id: I9908ff4edbf2b0d961d25837a08a34e1417bbb02

upstream discussion).  Thus we run the output of yum through a small

commit_message:
Detect missing packages with yum

yum -y doesn't report an error when packages are missing (see [1] for
upstream discussion).  Thus we run the output of yum through a small
awk script looking for missing packages output.

The one change required for RHEL is that python-wsgiref is included in
the distro python, so doesn't need a separate package.

[1] https://bugzilla.redhat.com/show_bug.cgi?id=965567

Change-Id: I9908ff4edbf2b0d961d25837a08a34e1417bbb02

One Convergence Neutron Plugin l3 ext support

Adding support for l3 extensions and security-groups.

commit_message:
BigSwitch: Fix rest call in consistency watchdog

Fixes the rest call in the consistency watchdog
in the BigSwitch plugin that was causing it to
raise an exception.

Closes-Bug: #1289138
Change-Id: Id4dff993426573be6984eb1e8f6ef2aabfff0779

commit_message:
Fix unittest failure in radware lbaas driver

Issue greenthread.sleep(0) to switch greenthreads and wait
for vip to complete deletion

Change-Id: I46b0702b0df527965ecf94e334ed3327f408a05c

commit_message:
Fix user guide typos and text

  Updated ubuntu user to format with <literal> in
  /openstack-manuals/doc/user-guide/section_dashboard_launch_instances.xml,
  and changed "username" to "user name."

  Updated "etc" to "and so on," changed "Heat" to "Orchestration,"
  and changed intro paragraph about Orchestration to match what's on the
  OpenStack getting started site in:
  /openstack-manuals/doc/user-guide/section_dashboard_stacks.xml

Change-Id: Ie33d9a31c9d8b1ada31bf1c226ccb92eb0c08f1f

commit_message:
Raise an error when no slug on tab group

When a tab group has no slug defined, it behaves in very strange
ways and the error is hard to find. This will make finding it much
easier.

Change-Id: I97c4cdc7a860e8c40ce17ee1a59384bbf85782ad
Closes-bug: 1288650

commit_message:
Updated flagmappings and tables for neutron

Import results of the autohelp.py tool for neutron.

Note: I used a non-published version of autohelp.py, with the following patches:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/79076/

commit_message:
Add missing OpenStack Compute tables

A number of tables were being generated but not listed in the guide and
have now been added. Additional edits were also made to ensure the
tables are listed alphabetically based on group name, this was largely
already being applied with one or two notable discrepancies.

commit_message:
Replaces exception re-raising in Hyper-V

In a few cases in the Hyper-V driver classes, generic exceptions
are getting caught, logged and a domain specific exception is raised.

This creates issues in identifying the exception cause programmatically
(e.g. in unit tests).

This patch enforces the usage of excutils.save_and_reraise_exception()

Closes-Bug: #1280363

Change-Id: I27cc54941c5f592ea567ccaa8fa369362da1427f

Convert cinder utils tests to use mock

Convert the tests using mox to use mock.  Also add several
new tests to increase overall test coverage.

Closes-bug: 1285905

I think we could mention this situation in several places. I initially added it to the installation guide because many people seem to perform their first installation in environments with rather limited resources. Even with minimal activity, the quantity of expired tokens quickly becomes large enough to impact performance. For example, the controller nodes in my lab with 2 GB of memory begin using swap space after a week or two which impacts all services. commit_message:
Add cron job to periodically flush expired tokens

By default, the Identity Service stores expired tokens in the database
indefinitely. While potentially useful for auditing in production
environments, the accumulation of expired tokens will considerably
increase database size and may decrease service performance,
particularly in test environments with limited resources. I added
a step to create a periodic task using 'cron' which calls
'keystone-manage token_flush' to purge expired token hourly.

Change-Id: Ie2bb4b03da25037426daa57edf084e9801a139fb
Closes-Bug: #1287962

recheck migrations'}, {'account_id': 1653, 'date': '2014-03-10 08:47:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

@Matt: I think that there are two issues here. The first is discussing the mail thread that you mentioned. The second is the issue that the patch set addresses. The former will still need to be done irrespective of which architecture we use. When there is a common shared datastore we will need to make sure that one threads actions do not cause havoc with anothers. It would, in my humble opinion. be a pity to block something like this. My two cents is that we can use something like until we decide what future steps we would like to take to address various architectural decisions.'}, {'account_id': 9555, 'date': '2014-03-10 10:15:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(5 inline comments)

I don't agree that this is stepping outside what it's reasonable for a driver to do. The driver is responsible for reading and writing data on a datastore, and doing that race-free requires locking. In this case the datastore is the vSphere API; in other drivers the datastore may be a shared filesystem or a storage array. If other drivers aren't locking, I suspect they contain similar races.

This change isn't an attempt to create a DLM; it's an attempt to implement shared locking on a datastore with very poor provision for it. Systems programming is full of obtuse little dances which achieve a particular necessary result, but which are sufficiently complex that they're normally abstracted into a library funcation, c.f. unix file descriptor passing and posix locking. In short, I don't think this is conceptually wrong.

However, I've given this quite a bit of thought over the weekend, and I'm not convinced we're going to be able to do this with the vSphere API. It *might* be possible to do simple mutual exclusion locking, however I don't think we could accept any solution which relied on a heartbeat. In my consulting days, I was once called out to diagnose a problem which turned out to result from a malfunctioning storage array with an average service time of over 5 seconds. There are other ways you can occasionally get arbitrarily large delays too, for example due to network interruption or swapping. The problem here is one of safety, because after the affected machine unpauses it has no idea it no longer has a lock. I believe a safe implementation would have to rely on session timeouts and/or forcibly ending another session if taking an already-held lock.

This implementation also suffers from a non-atomic interaction, which would itself require protection. That is, the creation of the lock itself, and the creation of the heatbeat. This isn't a simple problem.

However, I don't think even this is enough. In the image cache case we really need a read/write lock. If we only had a simple exclusion lock, then multiple spawns against the same image would be unnecessarily serialised, which would be unacceptable. This, I think, will require a semaphore, which is another level of complexity.

I don't think it's currently worth writing any code for this until we've hashed out an architecture which we think will work. My current feeling, though, is that the vSphere API is going to be insufficient and we're going to end up using a DLM. If we do, it should be the same DLM used by the rest of Nova."}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2014-03-10 15:08:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Do not merge

The whole point of the Nova architecture is to not need or use a DLM. If we come back to OpenStack basic design tenants, this is headed the wrong direction - https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/BasicDesignTenets

I think this is way beyond what should be considered inside a nova driver, and definitely not where we should be spending brain power post Feature Freeze.

Let's bring this up at summit instead, because I think we really need a more real discussion on the level of cluster complexity that is now being hidden inside of a nova driver which was really designed to be a per host model."}, {'account_id': 1653, 'date': '2014-03-10 19:51:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Abandoned

No longer needed'}]

[{'created': '2014-03-09 15:18:28.000000000', 'message': "VMware: add shared datastore locking utiliity

The patch set enables locking via the datastore. This will
enable more than one compute node to perform aging.

The code solution is self healing, that is, if a compute node that
takes a lock fails then another compute node can detect that and
take over the lock if necessary.

When a lock is take a 'heartbeat' will indicate that it is still
being used by the compute node. If the 'heartbeat' is no longer
updated then another compuet node may take over the lock.

Change-Id: Iaf28623cac5b7c4d107b05aef103c96c31e6f6ae
"}, {'created': '2014-03-09 15:44:49.000000000', 'message': 'VMWare: ensure that image aging does not race with spawn

The patch enables multiple compute nodes to run in parallel.
This ensures that the compute nodes can spawn and age
safely without any race conditions.

The code is self healing, that is, if a compute node is accessing
an image and it fails, then another compute node will be able to
access that image. This can be either spawning or aging.

Change-Id: Iaf28623cac5b7c4d107b05aef103c96c31e6f6ae
'}]
commit_message:
VMWare: ensure that image aging does not race with spawn

The patch enables multiple compute nodes to run in parallel.
This ensures that the compute nodes can spawn and age
safely without any race conditions.

The code is self healing, that is, if a compute node is accessing
an image and it fails, then another compute node will be able to
access that image. This can be either spawning or aging.

Change-Id: Iaf28623cac5b7c4d107b05aef103c96c31e6f6ae

commit_message:
Enable marconi-server to run when USE_SCREEN=false

This patch,
1. adds log_file option to marconi.conf
2. redirects the output from marconi-server, in the same precedent
set by another project.

Change-Id: Ib273a03625d5a4edf8bb3ed7d522d2b087975acd

commit_message:
Nova ironic driver to retry on HTTP 503

The commit 0ddab4236753f33fe5f828afb76f7148fd014b8f fixed the Ironic
API to return HTTP 503 (Service unavailable) when a request can't be
completed because the service was temporary unavailable, before the
API was returning HTTP 409 (Conflict) for such cases. The nova ironic
driver was looking at HTTP 409 in order to retry a request, this commit
fix the retry mechanism on the nova ironic driver making it look at the
HTTP 503 instead.

Change-Id: Ia0ecb40fee55b28a9865def7ba9f8a29afc889ba
